messages.content: Calm down and I'll tell you what to do, okay?
Okay, and you said she's having a seizure?
Okay, okay, calm down. Take a deep breath. I'm going to get an ambulance over there, but I need you to calm down, okay?
The first thing you need to do is make sure that there's nothing around your mom that's going to hurt her. Clear the area so when she's having a seizure, she doesn't hurt herself, okay?
Okay, don't put anything in her mouth. Don't try to hold her down. Just let her have the seizure. She's going to be just fine, okay?
Once she stops shaking, I need you to check her breathing for me, okay?
Is she coming out of it?
I don't know. She's not breathing.
Okay. Does anybody there know CPR?
Who knows CPR? Who can I talk to to give CPR instructions?
No one knows. My dad's not home.
Okay, what I need you to do is listen to me, and I'll tell you what to do, okay?
Turn her flat on her back.
Go ahead and kneel down by her side. You said she's not breathing, right?
Okay, pinch her nose closed with one hand, and with the other hand, lift her chin up to tilt the head back.
Now, completely cover her mouth with your mouth and give her two big breaths, okay?
Is she trying to breathe on her own?
Is there anything in her throat, like vomit or phlegm?
Is air getting into her lungs? Is her chest rising and falling?
Is she moving, coughing, or breathing normally yet?
Oh, no, she's starting to breathe normally.
Okay, then roll her onto her side and stay with her. Keep her on her side.
Mom. He gave her two breaths, and I could hear gurgling.
I can't get her on her side.
Can you turn her head to the side so she doesn't choke?
She's moaning. Yes, she's on the bed.
Tell her the ambulance is on the way. Stay with her and I'll stay on the phone, okay?
Has she ever had a seizure before?
Is she allergic to anything, like a bee sting, or did she hit her head recently?
When did she hit her head? Today?
No, she has a brain injury.
Okay. We're going to help her. We'll be there in just a minute. You said 905 Dennery Lane?
You're doing a very good job, okay? What's your phone number?
Okay. How is your mom? Is she still breathing?
Who else is there with you?
Just me and my little brother.
How old is your little brother?
He's 5. We were just out front when she dropped.
Are you going to send an ambulance?
Yes, they're on their way. When did your mom get her brain injury?
April 5th of this year or last year?
Okay. You've never seen her have a seizure before?
Is your mom ok? Is she coming around?
Kind of. Her eyes are open.
Can you talk to her? Is she able to answer you?
And you have her rolled over?
Is her breathing normal? Is her chest rising and falling?
I think the police or the ambulance are there now.
If that's the police or the firemen, go ahead and talk to them. I'm going to hang up now, okay?
